{"id":"d=origam-topic-2081//p=b7e29c1008ac4c5b9838a0e3816dbc15","tags":{"__document_id":["origam-topic-2081"],"__file_type":["text/plain"],"__file_id":["b0c7d9e40cc54bd69cac640dd74df56b"],"__file_part":["0fc7814d87fb45dfaf1196667b91fdc9"],"__part_n":["1"],"__sect_n":["0"],"source":["origam-community"],"category":["docs"],"categoryId":["8"],"topicId":["2081"],"url":["https://community.origam.com/t/data-page/2081"],"title":["Data Page"]},"payload":{"url":"","schema":"20231218A","file":"content.txt","text":" to the API in the HTTP request body you need to: \n \n Set  AllowPUT  to  True . \n Add a new ParameterMapping under the Data Page API with any name and MappedParameter empty. This will pass the body to the API. \n Send the request under the same URL you used to load the data, e.g. /api/invoice/1234 \n \n It is recommended to set  AllFields=True  in the source data structure entities otherwise concurrency exceptions can occur. \n The process then goes like this: \n \n When you send a PUT request to  /api/invoice/1234  first the old invoice no. 1234 is loaded from the database \n Then the data of the old invoice are updated with the data sent with the request \n Then the changes are saved to the database. \n \n If you want to insert data you need to provide a parameter under which no invoice will be loaded, e.g.  /api/invoice/new . The first step which loads the record will find nothing resulting in INSERTs into the database. \n The server has to be set to run all managed modules for all requests, otherwise put operation will fail because of unauthorized access. \n  \u003Cmodules runAllManagedModulseForAllRequest=\u0022true\u0022\u003E  \n  \u003C/modules\u003E  \n   Pagination \n You can use built-in data pagination functions to return pages of data instead of whole lists. See  LoadData Method  for details. \n You need to map the input parameters to the internal  _pageNumber  and  _pageSize  parameters the same way you would map other parameters. See Kendo Mobile - Pagination And Server-Side Filtering for an example. \n   Deleting Data \n When you want to send a request that will delete data you need to: \n \n Set AllowDELETE to True \n Send a request to the URL, e.g.  /api/invoice/1234  \n The data will get loaded and then deleted. \n \n   Concurrency Handling \n As you see from the previous example there is no concurrency handling built-in and the last write wins. \n   Custom Filters \n If the  AllowCustomFilters  parameter is set to true, you can send custom filters and ordering in the request body. \n   Schema (summary) \n \n filter (string): JSON\u2011encoded filter expression (see structure below) \n filterLookups (object): lookup values keyed by columnId \n ordering (array): list of { columnId, direction } \n \n   filter (string) \n filter is a string containing a bracketed expression. Build it as a JSON array and then serialize it to a string. \n   Structure \n [\u201C\u003CcolumnId\u003E\u201D, \u201C\u003Coperator\u003E\u201D, \u003Cvalue\u003E] \n Examples: \n [\u201Cname\u201D, \u201Cgt\u201D, \u201CJohn Doe\u201D] \n[\u201Cname\u201D, \u201Ccontains\u201D, \u201CJohn Doe\u201D] \n[\u201Cname\u201D, \u201Ceq\u201D, null] \n   Logical grouping (must use $AND / $OR) \n [\u201C$AND\u201D, \n[\u201C$OR\u201D, [\u201Ccity_name\u201D, \u201Ccontains\u201D, \u201CWash\u201D], [\u201Cname\u201D, \u201Ccontains\u201D, \u201CSmith\u201D]], \n[\u201Cage\u201D, \u201Cgte\u201D, 18], \n[\u201Cid\u201D, \u201Cin\u201D, [\u201Cf2\u201D, \u201Cf3\u201D, \u201Cf4\u201D]] \n] \n   in / between use a nested array \n [\u201Cage\u201D, \u201Cbetween\u201D, [18, 80]] \n[\u201Cname\u201D, \u201Cin\u201D, [\u201CTom\u201D, \u201CJane\u201D, \u201CDavid\u201D]] \n   Supported operator list \n Equality / comparison \n \n eq, neq \n gt, lt, gte, lte \n \n String \n \n starts, nstarts \n ends, nends \n contains, ncontains \n \n Set / range \n \n in, nin \n between, nbetween \n \n Null \n \n null, nnull \nUse null or nnull with a literal null value, e.g. [\u201Cname\u201D,\u201Cnull\u201D,null]. \n \n Logical (grouping only) \n \n $AND, $OR \n \n  Notes  \nThere is no not operator. Negation is expressed with the n* variants (ncontains, nin, nnull, etc.). \n   filterLookups (object) \n A map of columns names to the lookup ids. Use this when the filter targets a lookup field. Keys must be the same columnId used in filter, values must be UUID strings. \n Example: \n \u201CfilterLookups\u201D: { \n\u201CrefTagInputSourceId\u201D: \u201C991a8bec-5169-4506-9457-7f91c27bb5fd\u201D \n} \n   ordering (array) \n Ordered list of sort rules applied after filtering. ","vector_provider":"AI.Ollama.OllamaTextEmbeddingGenerator","vector_generator":"__","last_update":"2026-04-29T00:22:59"},"vector":[-0.022630772,-0.006891316,-0.036959484,0.043709997,0.0011027326,-0.024612105,0.006737297,-0.029384628,-0.0139917135,0.016718704,-0.0036623606,0.033718448,-0.008418233,0.044912063,-0.04028642,0.011747518,-0.03939724,-0.006415045,0.023347467,0.030448366,-0.040486723,0.02242602,-0.0040456224,-0.0005332446,0.006592774,0.023499964,-0.03173259,-0.014990567,-0.038949426,-0.02245337,0.018873537,-0.0033212218,-0.017139388,-0.048014782,-0.010278582,-0.041089978,-0.009093084,-0.01889534,-0.027196426,0.029313283,0.0033491838,-0.029158385,-0.013752232,-0.031820808,0.06416542,-0.027578222,-0.020678371,-0.015630297,-0.010788884,-0.04820508,-0.041413866,-0.014648294,0.0079599535,-0.042260986,-0.022165673,0.043439258,0.007237885,0.0018234262,-0.057573754,0.010942902,-0.0193217,-0.0009380698,-0.022510558,-0.05469852,-0.0010166196,0.01058365,-0.035338137,0.007610677,-0.024526354,-0.032043815,0.015191337,0.032414544,-0.056278046,-0.010193507,-0.04915297,-0.0013152058,0.024998378,-0.012707079,-0.035055984,-0.024147488,-0.014376916,-0.055998698,0.015525314,-0.0297807,0.0047923056,-0.011097128,-0.01611326,0.025902266,0.0023514233,0.05657676,-0.0051388424,-0.004622647,0.04698772,-0.037699465,-0.0028055308,-0.04221904,-0.006136302,-0.002689834,0.019